what: Investigating Age or Divergence Category Specific Expression Level Distributions
title: Advanced Phylotranscriptomics Analyses
text: Gene expression levels fundamental aspect phylotranscriptomics studies. detail, phylotranscriptomic measures aim quantify expression intensity genes deriving common age divergence categories detect stages evolutionary constraints. Hence, gene expression distribution age divergence categories well differences within stages categories allow us investigate age (PS) divergence (DS) category specific contribution corresponding transcriptome. purpose, PlotCategoryExpr() aims visualize expression level distribution phylostratum time point experiment barplot, dot plot, violin plot enabling users quantify age (PS) divergence (DS) category specific contribution corresponding transcriptome. way visualizing gene expression distribution age (PS) divergence (DS) category developmental stages experiments allows users detect specific age divergence categories contributing significant levels gene expression underlying biological process (transcriptome). resulting boxplot illustrates log expression levels phylostratum developmental stage. Additionally, Kruskal-Wallis Rank Sum Test well Benjamini & Hochberg p-value adjustment multiple comparisons performed (test.stat = TRUE) statistically quantify differences expression levels different age divergence categories. type analysis allows users detect stages experiments show high deviation age divergence category contributions overall transcriptome significant deviations age divergence categories, suggesting equal age divergence category contributions overall transcriptome. corresponding P-values printed console using following notation: ’*’ = P-Value ≤\leq 0.05 ’**’ = P-Value ≤\leq 0.005 ’***’ = P-Value ≤\leq 0.0005 ‘n.s.’ = significant = P-Value > 0.05 case developmental stages show significant differences phylostratum specific gene expression. Please notice users need define legendName argument PS DS specify whether input ExpressionSet PhyloExpressionSet (legendName = 'PS') DivergenceExpressionSet (legendName = 'DS'). Alternatively, users can investigate differences gene expression stages experiments age divergence category specifying type = 'stage-centered'. , Kruskal-Wallis Rank Sum Test (Benjamini & Hochberg p-value adjustment) quantifies whether gene expression distribution single age divergence category significantly changes throughout development experiments. type analysis allows users detect specific age divergence categories significantly change expression levels throughout development experiments. case, users observe PS3,5,7-9,11 show significant differences gene expression developmental stages suggesting contribution overall transcriptome remains constant throughout development. Finally, users can choose following plot types visualize expression distributions: Argument: distr.type distr.type = "boxplot" specification allows users visualize expression distribution PS DS boxplot. distr.type = "violin" specification allows users visualize expression distribution PS DS violin plot. distr.type = "dotplot" specification allows users visualize expression distribution PS DS dot plot. Together, studies performed PlotCategoryExpr() allow users conclude genes originating specific PS DS contribute significantly overall transcriptome genes originating different PS DS categories. specialized analyses PlotMeans(), PlotRE(), PlotBarRE(), TAI(), TDI(), etc. allow study exact mean expression patterns age divergence categories. Users notice far examples shown specified log.expr = TRUE illustrating boxplots based log2 expression levels. way visualization allows better visual comparisons age divergence categories. However, specifying log.expr = FALSE absolute expression levels visualized corresponding boxplot. Alternatively, instead specifying log.expr = TRUE users can directly pass log2 transformed expression levels PlotCategoryExpr() via tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample,log2) (log.expr = FALSE): expression level transformation, e.g. sqrt.

what: Computing the significant differences between gene expression distributions of PS or DS groups
title: Advanced Phylotranscriptomics Analyses
text: proposed Quint et al., 2012 cases users wish compare difference group specific expression levels using statistical test. purpose, PlotGroupDiffs() function performs test quantify statistical significance global expression level distributions groups PS DS. therefore allows users investigate significant groups PS DS significantly differ gene expression level distribution within specific developmental stages experiments. Analogous PlotRE() PlotMeans() function (see Introduction details), users need pass Groups PlotGroupDiffs() specifying groups shall compared. cases plot shall drawn resulting p-value shall returned users can specify plot.type = NULL argument receive p-values returned underlying test statistic. Optionally, users can also visualize difference expression level distributions groups PS/DS developmental stage specifying plot.type = "boxplot" argument. , use log2 transformed expression levels better visualization (tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample,log2)). Internally, PlotGroupDiffs() function performs Wilcoxon Rank Sum test quantify statistical significance PS/DS group expression. quantification allows users detect developmental stages significant expression level differences PS/DS groups. example chose genes originated evolution embryogenesis evolved plants (Group1 = PS1-3) versus genes originated evolution embryogenesis evolved plants (Group2 = PS4-12). result, observe indeed difference total gene expression groups significant throughout embryogenesis. terms P-value quantification observe P-value minimized towards phylotypic period. Hence, expression level difference studied PS groups maximized phylotypic period.
code: library(myTAI) data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  PlotGroupDiffs(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                Groups        = list(group_1 = 1:3,group_2 = 4:12),                legendName    = "PS",                plot.type     = "p-vals",                type          = "b",                lwd           = 6,                xlab          = "Ontogeny") library(myTAI) data(PhyloExpressionSetExample) # only receive the p-values without the corresponding plot PlotGroupDiffs(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                Groups        = list(group_1 = 1:3,group_2 = 4:12),                legendName    = "PS",                plot.type     = NULL) library(myTAI) data(PhyloExpressionSetExample) # visualize difference as boxplot PlotGroupDiffs(ExpressionSet = tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample,log2),                Groups        = list(group_1 = 1:3,group_2 = 4:12),                legendName    = "PS",                plot.type     = "boxplot")

title: Enrichment Analyses
text: Phylostratum Divergence Stratum enrichment analyses performed several studies correlate organ metabolic pathway evolution origin organ pathway specific genes (Sestak Domazet-Loso, 2015). detail, Phylostratum Divergence Stratum enrichment analyses can performed analogously Gene Ontology Kegg enrichment analyses study enrichment evolutionary age sequence divergence set selected genes entire genome/transcriptome. case specific age categories significantly - underrepresented selected gene set, assumptions potential correlations evolutionary origin particular organ metabolic pathway can implied. vignette use data set published Sestak Domazet-Loso, 2015 demonstrate perform enrichment analyses using myTAI.

title: Enrichment Analyses
text: PlotEnrichment() function implemented myTAI computes visualizes significance enriched (- underrepresented) Phylostrata Divergence Strata within input set process/tissue specific genes. detail function takes Phylostratum Divergence Stratum distribution genes stored input ExpressionSet background set Phylostratum Divergence Stratum distribution specific gene set performs Fisher’s exact test Phylostratum Divergence Stratum quantify statistical significance - -represented Phylostrata Divergence Strata within set selected genes. words, frequency distribution Phylostrata Divergence Strata complete sample compared frequency distribution Phylostrata Divergence Strata set selected genes - -representation visualized log-odds (odds), log-odd zero means frequency distributions equal (see also Sestak Domazet-Loso, 2015).

title: Enrichment Analyses
text: using PlotEnrichment() function, need download example data set Sestak Domazet-Loso, 2015. Download Phylostratigraphic Map D. rerio: Read *.xlsx file storing Phylostratigraphic Map D. rerio format use myTAI: Now, Drerio.PhyloMap stores Phylostratigraphic Map D. rerio used background set perform enrichment analyses PlotEnrichment().

text: Fisher test performed inside PlotEnrichment() assumes genes stored input ExpressionSet Phylostratigraphic Map/Divergence Map used define background set constructing test statistic. However, since cases test.set subset input ExpressionSet Phylostratigraphic Map/Divergence Map one also specify complete.bg argument remove test.set genes background set performing Fisher test visualization. following two examples allow users compare results retaining genes background set compared option remove test.set genes background set. Users notice although p-values change, qualitative result change. border line cases however, results might influence whether Phylostrata Divergence Strata denoted significantly enriched . always aware interpretation retaining removing test.set background set, options valid advantages disadvantages depend valid interpretation.
code: # complete.bg = TRUE (default) -> retain test.set genes in background set PlotEnrichment(Drerio.PhyloMap,                test.set     = Drerio.Brain.Genes,                measure      = "log-foldchange",                complete.bg  = TRUE,                use.only.map = TRUE,                legendName   = "PS") # complete.bg = FALSE -> remove test.set genes from background set PlotEnrichment(Drerio.PhyloMap,                test.set     = Drerio.Brain.Genes,                measure      = "log-foldchange",                complete.bg  = FALSE,                use.only.map = TRUE,                legendName   = "PS")

title: Gene Expression Analysis with `myTAI`
text: Welch t-test parametric test statistically quantify difference sample means cases assumption homogeneity variance (equal variances two populations) violated (Boslaugh, 2013). Welch t-test sufficient parameter test small sample sizes thus, used detect differentially expressed genes based p-values returned test statistic (Hahne et al., 2008). detail, test statistic computed follows: t=x‾1−x‾2s12n1+s22n2t = \frac{\bar{x}_1 - \bar{x}_2}{\sqrt{\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \frac{s_2^2}{n_2}}} x‾1\bar{x}_1 x‾2\bar{x}_2 sample means, s12s_1^2 s22s_2^2 sample variances, n1n_1 n2n_2 sample sizes. degrees freedom Welch’s t-test computed follows: df=(s12n1+s22n2)2s14n12(n1−1)+s24n22(n2−1)df = \frac{\big(\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \frac{s_2^2}{n_2}\big)^2}{\frac{s_1^4}{n_1^2 (n_1 - 1)} + \frac{s_2^4}{n_2^2 (n_2 - 1)}} perform sufficient Welch t-test following assumptions input data need fulfilled test whether two samples come populations equal means: Assumptions input data independent samples continuous data (approximate) normality Nevertheless, although cases log2 expression levels used perform Welch t-test assuming expression levels log-normal distributed approximates normal distribution infinity, cases small number replicates sufficient enough fulfill (approximate) normality assumption Welch t-test. Due fact, non-parametric, sampling based, generalized linear model based methods proposed quantify p-values differential expression. Nevertheless, DiffGenes() function implements Welch t-test detection differentially expressed genes, allowing users compare results recent DEG detection methods/methodologies also implemented DiffGenes(). title: Gene Expression Analysis with `myTAI`
text: Performing Welch t-test DiffGenes() can done specifying method = "t.test". Internally DiffGenes() performs two sided Welch t-test. means Welch t-test quantifies whether gene significantly differentially expressed, direction enrichment (-expressed -expressed). PhyloExpressionSetExample use following example stores absolute expression levels. case ExpressionSet also stores absolute expression levels (likely due ExpressionSet standard Phylotranscriptomics analyses), can use tf() function implemented myTAI transform absolute expression levels log2 expression levels performing DiffGenes() Welch t-test, e.g. tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample[1:5,1:8],log2). general, using log2 transformed expression levels input ExpressionSet DiffGenes() allows us (least) assume samples (replicate expression levels) used perform Welch t-test log-normal distributed therefore, somewhat approximate normal distributed. Please notice however, RNA-Seq data can include count values 0. transforming absolute counts log2 counts infinity values log2(0) = -Inf produced therefore, p-value computations possible. avoid case either remove RNA-Seq count values 0 input dataset using Expressed() function (see section Filter Expressed Genes), e.g. pass tf(Expressed(PhyloExpressionSetExample[1:5,1:8], cut.= 1),log2) ExpressionSet argument DiffGenes() shift count values constant value, e.g. pass tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample[1:5,1:8], function(x) log2(x + 1)) ExpressionSet argument DiffGenes(). Hahne et al., 2008 (p. 87) give nice example correcting multiple testing determine appropriate selection cut-offs. Now function computes statistical significance pattern derived corresponding combination replicates, e.g. 1.1, 2.1, 3.1 : p-value combination 1 1.1, 2.2, 3.1 : p-value combination 2 1.1, 2.3, 3.1 : p-value combination 3 1.2, 2.1, 3.1 : p-value combination 4 1.2, 2.1, 3.1 : p-value combination 5 1.2, 2.1, 3.1 : p-value combination 6 1.3, 2.1, 3.1 : p-value combination 7 1.3, 2.2, 3.1 : p-value combination 8 1.3, 2.3, 3.1 : p-value combination 9 … procedure yields 27 p-values 333^3 (nmn^m) replicate combinations, nn denotes number developmental stages mm denotes number replicates per stage. Note case users large amount stages/experiments large amount replicates computation time increase nmn^m. 11 stages 4 replicates, 4114^{11} = 4194304 p-values computed. p-value computation based permutation test running 1,000,10,000,...1,000, 10,000, ... permutations. aware might take time. p-value vector returned function can used plot p-values see whether critical value α\alpha exceeded (e.g. α=0.05\alpha = 0.05). code: # load a standard PhyloExpressionSet data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  # we assume that the PhyloExpressionSetExample # consists of 3 developmental stages # and 2 replicates for stage 1, 3 replicates for stage 2, # and 2 replicates for stage 3 # FOR REAL ANALYSES PLEASE USE: permutations = 1000 or 10000 # BUT NOTE THAT THIS TAKES MUCH MORE COMPUTATION TIME p.vector <- CombinatorialSignificance(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                                       replicates    = c(2,3,2),                                       TestStatistic = "FlatLineTest",                                       permutations  = 100,                                       parallel      = FALSE) [1] 2.436296e-03 2.288593e-02 1.608399e-03 1.185615e-02 1.835306e-06 1.077012e-05  [7] 2.025515e-07 5.148342e-07 1.654885e-07 6.251145e-06 9.265520e-10 1.047479e-06 any(p.vector > 0.05) #> FALSE

text: Motivated discussion raised Piasecka et al., 2013, influence gene expression transformation global phylotranscriptomic patterns seem negligible. Hence, different transformations can result qualitatively different TAI TDI patterns. Initially, TAI TDI formulas defined absolute expression levels. using initial TAI TDI formulas transformed expression levels can result qualitatively different patterns compared non-transformed expression levels, might also belong different class models, since different valid expression level transformation functions result different patterns. purpose tf() function allow user study qualitative impact different transformation functions global TAI TDI pattern, subsequent phylotranscriptomic analysis. examples using PhyloExpressionSetExample data set show using common gene expression transformation functions: log2 (Quackenbush, 2001 2002), sqrt (Yeung et al., 2001), boxcox, inverse hyperbolic sine transformation, transformation results qualitatively different patterns. Nevertheless, resulting pattern statistical significance can tested using either FlatLineTest(), ReductiveHourglassTest(), EarlyConservationTest() (Drost et al., 2015) quantify significance observed patterns. tf() function takes standard PhyloExpressionSet DivergenceExpressionSet transformation function returns corresponding ExpressionSet transformed gene expression levels. transforming ExpressionMatrix PhyloExpressionSetExample using different transformation functions, resulting phylotranscriptomic patterns qualitatively differ:

title: Introduction to the myTAI package
text: first measure named Transcriptome Age Index (TAI) introduced Domazet-Loso Tautz, 2010 represents weighted arithmetic mean transcriptome age corresponding developmental stage s. TAIs=∑=1npsi*eis∑=1neisTAI_s = \sum_{= 1}^n \frac{ps_i * e_{}}{\sum_{= 1}^n e_{}} psips_i denotes phylostratum assignment gene ii eise_{} denotes gene expression level gene ii developmental time point ss. lower value TAI describes older transcriptome age, whereas higher value TAI denotes younger transcriptome age. following figure shows TAI computations seven stages . thaliana embryo development. x-axis shows seven stages . thaliana embryo development y-axis shows corresponding mean transcriptome age (TAI) value. lower TAI value older mean transcriptome age higher TAI value younger mean transcriptome age. interpretation TAI values y-axis given next figure.  example, TAI value 3.5 quantifies genes contribute transcriptome particular stage emerged average phylostratum 3 phylostratum 4. Due nature arithmetic mean, value represent true origin individual genes, thus TAI measure helpful screen stages express (average) older younger genes. Subsequent analyses mean expression age categories, relative expression levels, gene expression level distributions age category reveal exact genes age categories generate overall TAI value. obtain detailed overview age categories contribute much developmental stage, gene expression level distributions age category developmental stage can visualized (using PlotCategoryExpr() function). figure shows developmental stages, genes coming PS1-3 (average) expressed genes coming PS4-12. Interestingly, gene expression level distributions PS4-12 become equally distributed towards Torpedo stage marked conserved stage TAI analysis. general trend can visualized using PlotMeans() function. , users observe indeed PS1-3 genes (average) higher expressed PS4-12 genes. Using linear transformation mean expression levels interval [0,1][0,1] (Quint et al., 2012 Drost et al., 2015) can compare mean expression patterns Phylostrata independent actual mean expression magnitude. relative expression level 0 denotes minimum mean expression level compared stages relative expression level 1 denotes maximum mean expression level compared stages. following figure illustrates average gene expression profile phylostratum. Users observe, PS4-12 genes -regulated towards Torpedo stage (marked conserved TAI analysis) -regulated Torpedo stage. cluster gene expression levels PS4-12 genes categorize . thaliana embryogenesis three developmental modules (early, mid, late) cluster young genes (PS4-12) according fold-change pattern: High-Low-Low, High-Low-High, Low-Low-High. result, find two distinct sets young genes: High-high-low low-low-high. Almost none genes high-low-high pattern. Finally, users can perform KEGG GO Term enrichment analyses obtain annotated functions gene sets.
code: data(PhyloExpressionSetExample) # Plot the Transcriptome Age Index of a given PhyloExpressionSet  # Test Statistic : Flat Line Test (default) PlotSignature( ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                measure       = "TAI",                 TestStatistic = "FlatLineTest",                xlab          = "Ontogeny",                 ylab          = "TAI" ) data(PhyloExpressionSetExample) # category-centered visualization of PS  # specific expression level distributions (log-scale) PlotCategoryExpr(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                      legendName    = "PS",                      test.stat     = TRUE,                      type          = "category-centered",                      distr.type    = "boxplot",                      log.expr      = TRUE) data(PhyloExpressionSetExample) # plot evolutionary old PS (PS1-3) vs # evolutionary young PS (PS4-12) PlotMeans(PhyloExpressionSetExample,           Groups = list(c(1:3), c(4:12)),            legendName = "PS",           adjust.range = TRUE) data(PhyloExpressionSetExample) # plot evolutionary old PS (PS1-3) vs # evolutionary young PS (PS4-12) PlotRE(PhyloExpressionSetExample,           Groups = list(c(1:3), c(4:12)),            legendName = "PS",           adjust.range = TRUE)

text: case observed phylotranscriptomic pattern significantly deviates flat line also visually resembles hourglass shape, one can obtain p-value quantifying statistical significance visual hourglass pattern based ReductiveHourglassTest (?ReductiveHourglassTest). Since ReductiveHourglassTest defined priori biological knowledge (Drost et al., 2015), modules argument within ReductiveHourglassTest() function needs specified. Three modules need specified: early-module, phylotypic module (mid), late-module. example divide . thaliana embryo development stored within PhyloExpressionSetExample following three modules: early = stages 1 - 2 (Zygote Quadrant) mid = stages 3 - 5 (Globular, Heart, Torpedo) late = stages 6 - 7 (Bent Mature) corresponding p-value p_rht now denotes p-value returned ReductiveHourglassTest different p-value returned FlatLineTest (p_flt). make sure correct modules selected perform ReductiveHourglassTest, users can use shaded.area argument visualize chosen modules: Note defining priori knowledge ReductiveHourglassTest using modules argument, modules need start stage 1, …, N correspond column position PhyloExpressionSet/DivergenceExpressionSet contrast start position 3, … N + 2. biological context, always clear stages define early, mid, late modules. animal embryogenesis, suggested choose early, mid, late modules according morphological conservation animal embryos (e.g. mid-stage vertebrate embryos seem morphologically conserved). plants, contrast morphological conservation reported thus average expression embryo defective genes used define modules (Drost et al. 2015).
code: # Plot the Transcriptome Age Index of a given PhyloExpressionSet  # Test Statistic : Reductive Hourglass Test PlotSignature( ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                measure       = "TAI",                TestStatistic = "ReductiveHourglassTest",                modules       = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7),                xlab          = "Ontogeny",                 ylab          = "TAI" ) # Visualize the phylotypic period used for the Reductive Hourglass Test PlotSignature( ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                measure       = "TAI",                TestStatistic = "ReductiveHourglassTest",                modules       = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7),                shaded.area   = TRUE,                 xlab          = "Ontogeny",                 ylab          = "TAI" )

text: third test statistic implemented myTAI package EarlyConservationTest. EarlyConservationTest tests whether observed phylotranscriptomic pattern follows low-high-high pattern (monotonically increasing function) supporting Early Conservation Model embryogenesis. Analogous ReductiveHourglassTest, EarlyConservationTest needs priori biological knowledge Drost et al., 2015. three modules specified EarlyConservationTest() function. Three modules need specified: early-module, phylotypic module (mid), late-module. example divide . thaliana embryo development stored within PhyloExpressionSetExample following three modules: early = stages 1 - 2 (Zygote Quadrant) mid = stages 3 - 5 (Globular, Heart, Torpedo) late = stages 6 - 7 (Bent Mature) corresponding p-value p_ect now denotes p-value returned EarlyConservationTest different p-value returned FlatLineTest (p_flt) ReductiveHourglassTest (p_rht). Since present TAI pattern PhyloExpressionSetExample doesn’t support Early Conservation Hypothesis, p-value p_ect = 1. note defining priori knowledge EarlyConservationTest using modules argument, modules need start stage 1, …, N correspond column position PhyloExpressionSet/DivergenceExpressionSet contrast start position 3, … N + 2. obtain numerical TAI values, TAI() function can used:

title: Compute the Statistical Significance of Each Replicate Combination — CombinatorialSignificance
text: intention analysis validate exists sequence replicates (possible combination replicates) results non-significant pattern, initial pattern combined replicates shown significant. small Example: Assume PhyloExpressionSet stores 3 developmental stages 3 replicates measured stage. 9 replicates total denoted : 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, 2.1, 2.2, 2.3, 3.1, 3.2, 3.3. Now function computes statistical significance pattern derived corresponding combination replicates, e.g. 1.1, 2.1, 3.1 -> p-value combination 1 1.1, 2.2, 3.1  -> p-value combination 2 1.1, 2.3, 3.1 -> p-value combination 3 1.2, 2.1, 3.1 -> p-value combination 4 1.2, 2.1, 3.1 -> p-value combination 5 1.2, 2.1, 3.1 -> p-value combination 6 1.3, 2.1, 3.1 -> p-value combination 7 1.3, 2.2, 3.1 -> p-value combination 8 1.3, 2.3, 3.1 -> p-value combination 9 procedure yields 27 p-values \(3^3\) (\(n_stages^n_replicates\)) replicate combinations. Note, case large amount stages/experiments large amount replicates computation time increase \(n_stages^n_replicates\). 11 stages 4 replicates, 4^11 = 4194304 p-values computed. p-value computation based permutation test running 1000 permutations. aware might take time. p-value vector returned function can used plot p-values see whether critical value \(\alpha\) exeeded (e.g. \(\alpha = 0.05\)). function receives standard PhyloExpressionSet DivergenceExpressionSet object vector storing number replicates present stage experiment. Based arguments function computes possible replicate combinations using expand.grid function performs permutation test (either FlatLineTest replicate combination. permutation parameter function specifies number permutations shall performed permutation test. p-values computed, numeric vector storing corresponding p-values replicate combination returned. words, replicate combination present PhyloExpressionSet DivergenceExpressionSet object, TAI TDI pattern corresponding replicate combination tested statistical significance based underlying test statistic. function also able perform computations parallel using multicore processing. underlying statistical tests written C++ optimized fast computations.

title: Perform Reductive Early Conservation Test — EarlyConservationTest
text: Reductive Early Conservation Test aims statistically evaluate existence monotonically increasing phylotranscriptomic pattern based TAI TDI computations. corresponding p-value quantifies probability given TAI TDI pattern (phylotranscriptomics pattern) follow early conservation like pattern. p-value < 0.05 indicates corresponding phylotranscriptomics pattern indeed follow early conservation (low-high-high) shape.

title: Perform Reductive Early Conservation Test — EarlyConservationTest
code: EarlyConservationTest(   ExpressionSet,   modules = NULL,   permutations = 1000,   lillie.test = FALSE,   plotHistogram = FALSE,   runs = 10,   parallel = FALSE,   gof.warning = FALSE,   custom.perm.matrix = NULL )

title: Perform Reductive Early Conservation Test — EarlyConservationTest
text: ExpressionSet standard PhyloExpressionSet DivergenceExpressionSet object. modules list storing three elements: early, mid, late. element expects numeric vector specifying developmental stages experiments correspond module. example, module = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7) devides dataset storing seven developmental stages 3 modules. permutations numeric value specifying number permutations performed ReductiveHourglassTest. lillie.test boolean value specifying whether Lilliefors Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test shall performed quantify goodness fit. plotHistogram boolean value specifying whether Lillifor's Kolmogorov-Smirnov-Test shall performed test goodness fit approximated distribution, well additional plots quantifying significance observed phylotranscriptomic pattern. runs specify number runs performed goodness fit computations, case plotHistogram = TRUE. cases runs = 100 reasonable choice. Default runs = 10 (takes less computation time demonstration purposes). parallel performing runs parallel (takes cores multicore machine). gof.warning logical value indicating whether non significant goodness fit results printed warning. Default gof.warning = FALSE. custom.perm.matrix custom bootMatrix (permutation matrix) perform underlying test statistic. Default custom.perm.matrix = NULL.

title: Perform Reductive Early Conservation Test — EarlyConservationTest
text: list object containing list elements: p.value : p-value quantifying statistical significance (low-high-high pattern) given phylotranscriptomics pattern. std.dev : standard deviation N sampled phylotranscriptomics patterns developmental stage S. lillie.test : boolean value specifying whether Lillifors KS-Test returned p-value > 0.05, indicates fitting permuted scores normal distribution seems plausible.

title: Perform Reductive Early Conservation Test — EarlyConservationTest
text: reductive early conservation test permutation test based following test statistic. (1) set developmental stages partitioned three modules - early, mid, late - based prior biological knowledge. (2) mean TAI TDI value three modules T_early, T_mid, T_late computed. (3) two differences D1 = T_mid - T_early D2 = T_late - T_early calculated. (4) minimum D_min D1 D2 computed final test statistic reductive hourglass test. order determine statistical significance observed minimum difference D_min following permutation test performed. Based bootMatrix D_min calculated permuted TAI TDI profiles, approximated Gaussian distribution method moments estimated parameters returned fitdist, corresponding p-value computed pnorm given estimated parameters Gaussian distribution. goodness fit random vector D_min statistically quantified Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) test normality. case parameter plotHistogram = TRUE, multi-plot generated showing: (1) Cullen Frey skewness-kurtosis plot generated descdist. plot illustrates distributions seem plausible fit resulting permutation vector D_min. case reductive early conservation test normal distribution seemed plausible. (2) histogram D_min combined density plot plotted. D_min fitted normal distribution. corresponding parameters estimated moment matching estimation using fitdist function. (3) plot showing p-values N independent runs verify specific p-value biased specific permutation order. (4) barplot showing number cases underlying goodness fit (returned Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) test normality) shown significant (TRUE) significant (FALSE). allows quantify permutation bias implications goodness fit.

title: Perform Reductive Early Conservation Test — EarlyConservationTest
code: data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  # perform the early conservation test for a PhyloExpressionSet # here the prior biological knowledge is that stages 1-2 correspond to module 1 = early, # stages 3-5 to module 2 = mid (phylotypic module), and stages 6-7 correspond to # module 3 = late EarlyConservationTest(PhyloExpressionSetExample,                        modules = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7),                         permutations = 1000) #> The phylotranscriptomic pattern may not follow an early conservation pattern (low-mid-high or low-high-high). #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  #> $p.value #> [1] 0.9998591 #>  #> $std.dev #> [1] 0.05393337 0.05301197 0.05284169 0.05161798 0.05042234 0.05343254 0.05679332 #>  #> $lillie.test #> [1] NA #>    # use your own permutation matrix based on which p-values (EarlyConservationTest) # shall be computed custom_perm_matrix <- bootMatrix(PhyloExpressionSetExample,100) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>   EarlyConservationTest(PhyloExpressionSetExample,                        modules = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7),                         custom.perm.matrix = custom_perm_matrix) #> The phylotranscriptomic pattern may not follow an early conservation pattern (low-mid-high or low-high-high). #> $p.value #> [1] 0.9999901 #>  #> $std.dev #>     Zygote   Quadrant   Globular      Heart    Torpedo       Bent     Mature  #> 0.05246516 0.05312139 0.04978308 0.04955870 0.04989766 0.05093588 0.05233829  #>  #> $lillie.test #> [1] NA #>

code: data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  # remove genes that have an expression level below 8000  # in at least one developmental stage FilterConst <- Expressed(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                           cut.off       = 8000,                           method        = "const",                          comparison    = "below")                                dim(FilterConst) # check number of retained genes #> [1] 449   9  # remove genes that have an expression level below 8000  # in at least 3 developmental stages  # (in this case: ceiling(7/2) = 4 stages fulfilling the cut-off criteria) FilterMinSet <- Expressed(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                            cut.off       = 8000,                            method        = "min-set",                           comparison    = "below")                                 dim(FilterMinSet) # check number of retained genes #> [1] 24456     9   # remove expression levels that undercut AND exceed the cut.off criteria FilterMinSet <- Expressed(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,                            cut.off       = c(8000,12000),                            method        = "min-set",                           comparison    = "both")                                 dim(FilterMinSet) # text: list object containing list elements: p.value : p-value quantifying statistical significance (low-high-high pattern) given phylotranscriptomics pattern. std.dev : standard deviation N sampled phylotranscriptomics patterns developmental stage S. lillie.test : boolean value specifying whether Lillifors KS-Test returned p-value > 0.05, indicates fitting permuted scores normal distribution seems plausible.

title: Perform Reductive Late Conservation Test — LateConservationTest
text: reductive late conservation test permutation test based following test statistic. (1) set developmental stages partitioned three modules - early, mid, late - based prior biological knowledge. (2) mean TAI TDI value three modules T_early, T_mid, T_late computed. (3) two differences D1 = T_early - T_late D2 = T_mid - T_late calculated. (4) minimum D_min D1 D2 computed final test statistic reductive hourglass test. order determine statistical significance observed minimum difference D_min following permutation test performed. Based bootMatrix D_min calculated permuted TAI TDI profiles, approximated Gaussian distribution method moments estimated parameters returned fitdist, corresponding p-value computed pnorm given estimated parameters Gaussian distribution. goodness fit random vector D_min statistically quantified Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) test normality. case parameter plotHistogram = TRUE, multi-plot generated showing: (1) Cullen Frey skewness-kurtosis plot generated descdist. plot illustrates distributions seem plausible fit resulting permutation vector D_min. case reductive late conservation test normal distribution seemed plausible. (2) histogram D_min combined density plot plotted. D_min fitted normal distribution. corresponding parameters estimated moment matching estimation using fitdist function. (3) plot showing p-values N independent runs verify specific p-value biased specific permutation order. (4) barplot showing number cases underlying goodness fit (returned Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) test normality) shown significant (TRUE) significant (FALSE). allows quantify permutation bias implications goodness fit.

code: # load a standard PhyloExpressionSet data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)          # in a standard PhyloExpressionSet,  # column one and column two denote a standard  # phylostratigraphic map PhyloMap <- PhyloExpressionSetExample[ , 1:2]          # look at the phylostratigraphic map standard head(PhyloMap) #>   Phylostratum      GeneID #> 1            1 at1g01040.2 #> 2            1 at1g01050.1 #> 3            1 at1g01070.1 #> 4            1 at1g01080.2 #> 5            1 at1g01090.1 #> 6            1 at1g01120.1          # in a standard PhyloExpressionSet, column two combined  # with column 3 - N denote a standard ExpressionMatrix ExpressionMatrixExample <- PhyloExpressionSetExample[ , c(2,3:9)]          # these two data sets shall illustrate an example  # phylostratigraphic map that is returned # by a standard phylostratigraphy run, and a expression set  # that is the result of expression data analysis  # (background correction, normalization, ...)          # now we can use the MatchMap function to merge both data sets # to obtain a standard PhyloExpressionSet          PES <- MatchMap(PhyloMap, ExpressionMatrixExample)          # note that the function returns a head()  # of the matched gene ids to enable # the user to find potential mis-matches          # the entire procedure is analogous to merge()  # with two data sets sharing the same gene ids  # as column (primary key) PES_merge <- merge(PhyloMap, ExpressionMatrixExample)

Possible values can : altHypothesis = "greater" : contrast1 > contrast2 altHypothesis = "less" : contrast1 < contrast2 permutations numeric value specifying number permutations performed ReductiveHourglassTest. lillie.test boolean value specifying whether Lilliefors Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test shall performed quantify goodness fit. plotHistogram boolean value specifying whether Lillifor's Kolmogorov-Smirnov-Test shall performed test goodness fit approximated distribution, well additional plots quantifying significance observed phylotranscriptomic pattern. runs specify number runs performed goodness fit computations, case plotHistogram = TRUE. cases runs = 100 reasonable choice. Default runs = 10 (takes less computation time demonstration purposes). parallel performing runs parallel (takes cores multicore machine). gof.warning logical value indicating whether non significant goodness fit results printed warning. Default gof.warning = FALSE. custom.perm.matrix custom bootMatrix (permutation matrix) perform underlying test statistic. Default custom.perm.matrix = NULL.

code: data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  # perform the pairwise difference test for a PhyloExpressionSet # here the prior biological knowledge is that stages 1-2 correspond to contrast1, # stages 3-7 correspond to contrast 2. # We test whether TAI in contrast1 is greater than contrast 2. PairwiseTest(PhyloExpressionSetExample,          modules = list(contrast1 = 1:2, contrast2 = 3:7),           altHypothesis = "greater",          permutations = 1000) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  #> $p.value #> [1] 0.01971706 #>  #> $std.dev #> [1] 0.05614200 0.05508994 0.05334782 0.05143772 0.05121888 0.05221399 0.05667816 #>  #> $lillie.test #> [1] NA #>   # We can also test whether TAI in contrast1 is less than contrast 2. PairwiseTest(PhyloExpressionSetExample,          modules = list(contrast1 = 1:2, contrast2 = 3:7),           altHypothesis = "less",          permutations = 1000) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  #> $p.value #> [1] 0.973595 #>  #> $std.dev #> [1] 0.05555567 0.05472251 0.05274843 0.05209187 0.05074195 0.05208817 0.05569443 #>  #> $lillie.test #> [1] NA #>   # if we only want to test whether TAI in stage 1 (contrast 1) is greater than stage 3 (contrast 2). PairwiseTest(PhyloExpressionSetExample,          modules = list(contrast1 = 1, contrast2 = 2),           altHypothesis = "greater",          permutations = 1000) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  #> $p.value #> [1] 0.3856208 #>  #> $std.dev #> [1] 0.05568058 0.05449264 0.05283244 0.05168838 0.05033825 0.05185507 0.05587415 #>  #> $lillie.test #> [1] NA #>   # use your own permutation matrix based on which p-values (PairwiseTest) # shall be computed custom_perm_matrix <- bootMatrix(PhyloExpressionSetExample,100) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  # We test whether TAI in contrast1 is greater than contrast 2. PairwiseTest(PhyloExpressionSetExample,          modules = list(contrast1 = 1:2, contrast2 = 3:7),           altHypothesis = "greater",          custom.perm.matrix = custom_perm_matrix) #> $p.value #> [1] 0.04031736 #>  #> $std.dev #>     Zygote   Quadrant   Globular      Heart    Torpedo       Bent     Mature  #> 0.05655089 0.05535914 0.05549875 0.05317636 0.04994245 0.05009926 0.05629529  #>  #> $lillie.test #> [1] NA #>

title: Plot the Transcriptome Age Index or Transcriptome Divergence Index — PlotPattern
text: function computes permutation test quantifying statistical significance prensent phylotranscriptomics pattern. user can choose FlatLineTest, ReductiveHourglassTest, EarlyConservationTest. FlatLineTest tests significant deviation flat line. period stage significantly deviates flat line, might governed stronger selective pressure (terms natural selection) compared stages periods development. ReductiveHourglassTest specificly tests statistical significance molecular hourglass pattern (high-low-high pattern) prior biological knowlegde. corresponding p-value printed within plot (default) specifies statistical significance chosen test statistic. EarlyConservationTest specificly tests statistical significance low-high-high pattern (monotonically increasing function) prior biological knowlegde. corresponding p-value printed within plot (default) specifies statistical significance chosen test statistic. x-axis denotes developmental series (time course / experiments / ontogeny) input ExpressionSet y-axis denotes corresponding mean transcriptome age value (TAI TDI) given ExpressionSet. Furthermore, grey lines actual phylotranscriptomics pattern denotes standard deviations TAI TDI values estimated bootMatrix. low mean transcriptome age value denotes evolutionary older transcriptome active corresponding periods, whereas high mean transcriptome age value denotes evolutionary younger transcriptome active corresponding periods. mean transcriptome divergence, low mean transcriptome divergence value denotes conserved transcriptome active (two species), whereas high mean transcriptome divergence value denotes divergent transcriptome active (two species) - terms protein-sequence substitution rates. function useful fastly plot TAI TDI profile given PhyloExpressionSet DivergenceExpressionSet object statistical significance corresponding pattern. Internally function calls several graphics functions, plot, axis, legend. ellipsis argument ... graphics specific arguments can defined. Internally function specific arguments e.g. plot, axis, legend detected passed corresponding function. Hence, calling function PlotPattern, one can specify arguments plot axis legend .... case prior biological knowledge present specific period development, shaded.area argument can set TRUE function use values stored mid argument draw shaded area within corresponding period development.

title: Plot the Transcriptome Age Index or Transcriptome Divergence Index — PlotPattern
text: Hajk-Georg Drost

title: Plot the Transcriptome Age Index or Transcriptome Divergence Index — PlotPattern
code: # load PhyloExpressionSet data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  # only visualize the TAI profile without any test statistics... # this is equavalent to performing: plot(TAI(PhyloExpressionSetExample), type = "l", lwd = 6) PlotPattern(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,             TestStatistic = NULL,             type          = "l",             xlab          = "Ontogeny",             ylab          = "TAI",             lwd           = 9)   # the simplest example of plotting the TAI profile of a given PhyloExpressionSet: # In this case (default) the FlatLineTest will be performed to quantify # the statistical significance of the present TAI pattern and will be drawn as 'p = ... ' # in the plot  PlotPattern(ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,              TestStatistic = "FlatLineTest",             permutations  = 100,              type          = "l",              xlab          = "Ontogeny",              ylab          = "TAI",              lwd           = 9) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  #>  #> Total runtime of your permutation test: 0.024  seconds. #>  #> -> We recommended using at least 20000 permutations to achieve a sufficient permutation test.   # an example performing the ReductiveHourglassTest and printing the p-value # and shaded area of the presumptive phylotypic period into the plot # Here the 'p = ...' denotes the p-value that is returned by the ReductiveHourglassTest  PlotPattern(             ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,             TestStatistic = "ReductiveHourglassTest",             modules       = list(early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7),              permutations  = 100,              p.value       = TRUE,              shaded.area   = TRUE,              xlab          = "Ontogeny",              ylab          = "TAI",              type          = "l",              lwd           = 9) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>    # testing for early conservation model  PlotPattern( ExpressionSet = PhyloExpressionSetExample,              TestStatistic = "EarlyConservationTest",             modules        = list(early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7),              permutations   = 100,             p.value        = TRUE,              shaded.area    = TRUE,              xlab           = "Ontogeny",              ylab           = "TAI",              type           = "l",              lwd            = 9) #> The phylotranscriptomic pattern may not follow an early conservation pattern (low-mid-high or low-high-high). #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>                 # use your own permutation matrix custom_perm_matrix <- bootMatrix(PhyloExpressionSetExample,100) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>   PlotPattern(ExpressionSet      = PhyloExpressionSetExample,              TestStatistic      = "FlatLineTest",             custom.perm.matrix = custom_perm_matrix,              type               = "l",              xlab               = "Ontogeny",              ylab               = "TAI",              lwd                = 9) #>  #> -> We recommended using at least 20000 permutations to achieve a sufficient permutation test.

title: Plot Relative Expression Levels — PlotRE
text: function computes age category corresponding relative expression profile. age category corresponding relative expression profile computed follows: $$f_js = ( e_js - e_j min ) / ( e_j max - e_j min )$$ \(e_j min\) \(e_j max\) denote minimum/maximum mean expression level phylostratum j  developmental stages s. linear transformation corresponds shift \(e_j min\) subsequent shrinkage \(e_j max - e_j min\). result, relative expression level \(f_js\) developmental stage s minimum \(e_js\) 0, relative expression level \(f_js\) developmental stage s maximum \(e_js\) 1, relative expression levels \(f_js\) stages s range 0 1, accordingly.

what: Transform to Relative Expression Levels — RE
title: Transform to Relative Expression Levels — RE
text: function computes relative expression profiles given gene expression set. relative expression profile computed follows: $$f_s = ( e_s - e_min ) / ( e_max - e_min )$$ \(e_min\) \(e_max\) denote minimum/maximum mean expression level  developmental stages s. linear transformation corresponds shift \(e_min\) subsequent shrinkage \(e_max - e_min\). result, relative expression level \(f_s\) developmental stage s minimum \(e_s\) 0, relative expression level \(f_s\) developmental stage s maximum \(e_s\) 1, relative expression levels \(f_s\) stages s range 0 1, accordingly.

what: Perform the Reductive Hourglass Test — ReductiveHourglassTest
title: Perform the Reductive Hourglass Test — ReductiveHourglassTest
text: Reductive Hourglass Test aims statistically evaluate existence phylotranscriptomic hourglass pattern based TAI TDI computations. corresponding p-value quantifies probability given TAI TDI pattern (phylotranscriptomics pattern) follow hourglass like shape. p-value < 0.05 indicates corresponding phylotranscriptomics pattern indeed follow hourglass (high-low-high) shape.

title: Perform the Reductive Hourglass Test — ReductiveHourglassTest
code: ReductiveHourglassTest(   ExpressionSet,   modules = NULL,   permutations = 1000,   lillie.test = FALSE,   plotHistogram = FALSE,   runs = 10,   parallel = FALSE,   gof.warning = FALSE,   custom.perm.matrix = NULL )

title: Perform the Reductive Hourglass Test — ReductiveHourglassTest
text: ExpressionSet standard PhyloExpressionSet DivergenceExpressionSet object. modules list storing three elements: early, mid, late. element expects numeric vector specifying developmental stages experiments correspond module. example, module = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7) devides dataset storing seven developmental stages 3 modules. permutations numeric value specifying number permutations performed ReductiveHourglassTest. lillie.test boolean value specifying whether Lilliefors Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test shall performed quantify goodness fit. plotHistogram boolean value specifying whether Lillifor's Kolmogorov-Smirnov-Test shall performed test goodness fit approximated distribution, well additional plots quantifying significance observed phylotranscriptomic pattern. runs specify number runs performed goodness fit computations, case plotHistogram = TRUE. cases runs = 100 reasonable choice. Default runs = 10 (takes less computation time demonstration purposes). parallel performing runs parallel (takes cores multicore machine). gof.warning logical value indicating whether non significant goodness fit results printed warning. Default gof.warning = FALSE. custom.perm.matrix custom bootMatrix (permutation matrix) perform underlying test statistic. Default custom.perm.matrix = NULL.

title: Perform the Reductive Hourglass Test — ReductiveHourglassTest
text: list object containing list elements: p.value : p-value quantifying statistical significance (high-low-high pattern) given phylotranscriptomics pattern. std.dev : standard deviation N sampled phylotranscriptomics patterns developmental stage S. lillie.test : boolean value specifying whether Lillifors KS-Test returned p-value > 0.05, indicates fitting permuted scores normal distribution seems plausible.

title: Perform the Reductive Hourglass Test — ReductiveHourglassTest
text: reductive hourglass test permutation test based following test statistic. (1) set developmental stages partitioned three modules - early, mid, late - based prior biological knowledge. (2) mean TAI TDI value three modules T_early, T_mid, T_late computed. (3) two differences D1 = T_early - T_mid D2 = T_late - T_mid calculated. (4) minimum D_min D1 D2 computed final test statistic reductive hourglass test. order determine statistical significance observed minimum difference D_min following permutation test performed. Based bootMatrix D_min calculated permuted TAI TDI profiles, approximated Gaussian distribution method moments estimated parameters returned fitdist, corresponding p-value computed pnorm given estimated parameters Gaussian distribution. goodness fit random vector D_min statistically quantified Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) test normality. case parameter plotHistogram = TRUE, multi-plot generated showing: (1) Cullen Frey skewness-kurtosis plot generated descdist. plot illustrates distributions seem plausible fit resulting permutation vector D_min. case Reductive Hourglass Test normal distribution seemed plausible. (2) histogram D_min combined density plot plotted. D_min fitted normal distribution. corresponding parameters estimated moment matching estimation using fitdist function. (3) plot showing p-values N independent runs verify specific p-value biased specific permutation order. (4) barplot showing number cases underlying goodness fit (returned Lilliefors (Kolmogorov-Smirnov) test normality) shown significant (TRUE) significant (FALSE). allows quantify permutation bias implications goodness fit.

text: Hajk-Georg Drost

title: Perform the Reductive Hourglass Test — ReductiveHourglassTest
code: data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  # perform the reductive hourglass test for a PhyloExpressionSet # here the prior biological knowledge is that stages 1-2 correspond to module 1 = early, # stages 3-5 to module 2 = mid (phylotypic module), and stages 6-7 correspond to # module 3 = late ReductiveHourglassTest(PhyloExpressionSetExample,                        modules = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7),                         permutations = 1000) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  #> $p.value #> [1] 1.53632e-08 #>  #> $std.dev #> [1] 0.05620014 0.05490952 0.05323798 0.05270313 0.05260379 0.05389659 0.05483547 #>  #> $lillie.test #> [1] NA #>    # use your own permutation matrix based on which p-values (ReductiveHourglassTest) # shall be computed custom_perm_matrix <- bootMatrix(PhyloExpressionSetExample,100) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>   ReductiveHourglassTest(PhyloExpressionSetExample,                      modules = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7),                      custom.perm.matrix = custom_perm_matrix) #> $p.value #> [1] 6.915043e-11 #>  #> $std.dev #>     Zygote   Quadrant   Globular      Heart    Torpedo       Bent     Mature  #> 0.05491497 0.05523176 0.05663849 0.05451059 0.05593353 0.05465526 0.05362093  #>  #> $lillie.test #> [1] NA #>

title: Compute the Transcriptome Age Index (TAI) — TAI

title: Compute the Transcriptome Age Index (TAI) — TAI
text: TAI measure represents weighted arithmetic mean (expression levels weights phylostratum value) evolutionary age categories denoted phylostra. $$TAI_s = \sum (e_is * ps_i) / \sum e_is$$ TAI_s denotes TAI value developmental stage s, e_is denotes gene expression level gene stage s, ps_i denotes corresponding phylostratum gene , \(= 1,...,N\) N = total number genes. Internally function calls C++ function cpp_TAI speed TAI computations.

title: Compute the Transcriptome Polymorphism Index (TPI) — TPI
text: TPI measure represents weighted arithmetic mean (expression levels weights) synonymous vs non-synonymous polymorphism ratios. $$TPI_s = \sum (e_is * P_N/N / ((P_S + 1) / S)) / \sum e_is$$ TPI_s denotes TPI value developmental stage s, e_is denotes gene expression level gene stage s, n denotes number genes, PN PS denote numbers non-synonymous synonymous polymorphisms, N S numbers nonsynonymous synonymous sites, respectively. what: Compute the Hourglass Score for the EarlyConservationTest — ecScore
title: Compute the Hourglass Score for the EarlyConservationTest — ecScore
text: function computes EarlyConservationTest score given TAI TDI pattern. reductive early conservation test permutation test based following test statistic. - set developmental stages partitioned three modules - early, mid, late - based prior biological knowledge. - mean TAI TDI value three modules T_early, T_mid, T_late computed. - two differences D1 = T_mid - T_early D2 = T_late - T_early calculated. - minimum D_min D1 D2 computed final test statistic reductive early conservation test. function ecScore computes D_min value given TAI TDI stored age_vals argument.

title: Compute the Hourglass Score for the EarlyConservationTest — ecScore
code: ecScore(age_vals, early, mid, late, profile.warn = FALSE)

title: Compute the Hourglass Score for the EarlyConservationTest — ecScore
text: age_vals numeric vector containing TAI TDI values developmental stage s. early numeric vector storing numeric stage values correspond early phase development. mid numeric vector storing numeric stage values correspond middle phase development. late numeric vector storing numeric stage values correspond late phase development. profile.warn boolean value indicating whether warning printed low-mid-high pattern followed.

title: Compute the Hourglass Score for the EarlyConservationTest — ecScore
text: numeric value representing early conservation score.

title: Compute the Hourglass Score for the EarlyConservationTest — ecScore
text: Hajk-Georg Drost

title: Compute the Hourglass Score for the EarlyConservationTest — ecScore
code: # read standard phylotranscriptomics data  data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  data(DivergenceExpressionSetExample)   # Example PhyloExpressionSet:   # compute the TAI profile  TAIs <- TAI(PhyloExpressionSetExample)   # compute the early conservation score for the TAI profile  ec_score <- ecScore(age_vals = TAIs,early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7)    # Example DivergenceExpressionSet:   # compute the TDI profile  TDIs <- TDI(DivergenceExpressionSetExample)   # compute the early conservation score for the TDI profile  ec_score <- ecScore(age_vals = TDIs,early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7)    # compute ecScore() vector from bootMatrix()  apply(bootMatrix(PhyloExpressionSetExample,10),1,ecScore,early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7) #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  #>            1            2            3            4            5            6  #>  0.012846111  0.005238153  0.018602515 -0.006213682  0.018621329 -0.030893780  #>            7            8            9           10  #> -0.020161766 -0.002020718 -0.057479369  0.014861284     # get warning if the expected pattern isn't followed  ec_score <- ecScore(age_vals = TAIs,early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7,profile.warn=TRUE) #> The phylotranscriptomic pattern may not follow an early conservation pattern (low-mid-high or low-high-high).

what: Compute the Pairwise Difference in TAI Score — pairScore
title: Compute the Pairwise Difference in TAI Score — pairScore
text: function computes PairwiseTest score given TAI TDI pattern. pair test permutation test based following test statistic. - PhyloExpressionSet partitioned contrast pairs - contrast1 contrast2 - based prior biological knowledge. prior knowledge include sexual, ecological genetic backgrounds. - mean TAI TDI value two contrasts contrast1 contrast2 computed. - pairwise differences D_constrast = contrast1 - contrast2 calculated final test statistic pair test, altHypothesis specified "greater". altHypothesis specified "less", sign D_constrast reversed. function pairScore computes D_contrast value given TAI TDI stored age_vals argument.

title: Compute the Pairwise Difference in TAI Score — pairScore
code: pairScore(age_vals, contrast1, contrast2, altHypothesis = NULL)

title: Compute the Pairwise Difference in TAI Score — pairScore
text: age_vals numeric vector containing TAI TDI values developmental stage s. contrast1 numeric vector storing numeric stage values correspond query contrast. contrast2 numeric vector storing numeric stage values correspond subject contrast. altHypothesis character string defining alternative hypothesis used quantify statistical significance present phylotranscriptomics pattern. Possible values can : altHypothesis = "greater" : contrast1 > contrast2 altHypothesis = "less" : contrast1 < contrast2

title: Compute the Pairwise Difference in TAI Score — pairScore
text: numeric value representing pair score.

title: Compute the Pairwise Difference in TAI Score — pairScore
text: Hajk-Georg Drost Jaruwatana Sodai Lotharukpong

title: Compute the Pairwise Difference in TAI Score — pairScore
code: # read standard phylotranscriptomics data  data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  data(DivergenceExpressionSetExample)   # Example PhyloExpressionSet:   # compute the TAI profile  TAIs <- TAI(PhyloExpressionSetExample)   # compute the pair score for the first two stages in the TAI profile  # we test whether TAI in contrast1 is greater than contrast 2.  pair_score <- pairScore(age_vals = TAIs,contrast1 = 1,contrast2 = 2,                          altHypothesis="greater")    # Example DivergenceExpressionSet:   # compute the TDI profile  TDIs <- TDI(DivergenceExpressionSetExample)   # compute the pair score for the first two stages in the TDI profile  # we test whether TDI in contrast1 is greater than contrast 2.  pair_score <- pairScore(age_vals = TDIs,contrast1 = 1,contrast2 = 2,                          altHypothesis="greater")    # compute pairScore() vector from bootMatrix()  apply(bootMatrix(PhyloExpressionSetExample,10),1,        pairScore,contrast1 = 1,contrast2 = 2, altHypothesis="greater") #>  #> [ Number of Eigen threads that are employed on your machine: 12 ] #>  #> [ Computing age assignment permutations for test statistic ... ] #>  [=========================================] 100%    #> [ Computing variances of permuted transcriptome signatures ... ] #>  #>            1            2            3            4            5            6  #>  0.009680977  0.008971025  0.017052149 -0.026414837 -0.022327672 -0.019311822  #>            7            8            9           10  #>  0.011474037  0.013211218 -0.026666449 -0.006799789

what: Compute the Reverse Hourglass Score for the Reverse Hourglass Test — reversehourglassScore
title: Compute the Reverse Hourglass Score for the Reverse Hourglass Test — reversehourglassScore
text: function reduces destruction hourglass shaped pattern single score value. Based given TAI TDI pattern given vector         divided three developmental modules: early, mid, late. corrisponding TAI TDI         values developmental module accumulated using scoringMethod argument ("max-min" "mean-mean"). detail: (1) given TAI TDI vector tai_profile tdi_profile, classify value tai_profile tdi_profile corresponding developmental module early, mid, late. (2) accumulate tai_profile tdi_profile values developmental module using arithmetic mean (mean) case scoringMethod = "mean-mean", accumulate tai_profile tdi_profile values developmental module using max early late module min mid module case scoringMethod = "max-min". (3) reduce three values developmental module computing difference : mid - early, mid - late. (4) two difference values referred a_early a_late. developmental module now accumulated representation value reduced one value using         method argument ("max", "min", "mean"). Given two accumulated values hourglass module: a_early a_late,         reduce two given values : "max": \(S = max{a_early,a_late}\) "min": \(S = min{a_early,a_late}\) "mean": \(S = mean{a_early,a_late}\) together results global score S. global score S returned function.

title: Compute the Reverse Hourglass Score for the Reverse Hourglass Test — reversehourglassScore
code: # read standard phylotranscriptomics data  data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  data(DivergenceExpressionSetExample)   # example PhyloExpressionSet:   # compute the TAI profile  TAIs <- TAI(PhyloExpressionSetExample)   # compute the global reverse hourglass destruction score   # for the TAIs profile using reduction method: mean(mean-mean)  reversehourglass_score <- reversehourglassScore(age_vals = TAIs,early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7,                      method = "mean",scoringMethod = "mean-mean")    # example DivergenceExpressionSet:   # compute the TDI profile  TDIs <- TDI(DivergenceExpressionSetExample)   # compute the global reverse hourglass destruction score for the TDIs profile   # using reduction method: mean(mean-mean)  reversehourglass_score <- reversehourglassScore(age_vals = TDIs,early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7,                      method = "mean",scoringMethod = "mean-mean")                        # get warning if the expected pattern isn't followed  reversehourglass_score <- reversehourglassScore(age_vals = TAIs,early = 1:2,mid = 3:5,late = 6:7,                      method = "mean",scoringMethod = "mean-mean",profile.warn=TRUE) #> The phylotranscriptomic pattern may not follow a reverse hourglass pattern (low-high-low).

title: Transform Gene Expression Levels — tf
text: Motivated dicussion raised Piasecka et al., 2013, influence gene expression transformation global phylotranscriptomics pattern seem negligible. Hence, different transformations can result qualitatively different TAI TDI patterns. Initially, TAI TDI formulas defined absolute expression levels. using initial TAI TDI formulas transformed expression levels might turn qualitatively different patterns compared non-transformed expression levels, might also belong different class models, since different valid expression level transformation functions result different patterns. purpose function allow user study qualitative impact different transformation functions global TAI TDI pattern, subsequent phylotranscriptomics analysis. examples using PhyloExpressionSetExample data set show using common gene expression transformation functions: log2 (Quackenbush, 2001 2002), sqrt (Yeung et al., 2001), boxcox, inverse hyperbolic sine transformation, transformation results qualitatively different patterns. Nevertheless, resulting pattern statistical significance can tested using either FlatLineTest ReductiveHourglassTest (Drost et al., 2014) quantify significance interest.

title: Transform Gene Expression Levels — tf
code: if (FALSE) { # \dontrun{ data(PhyloExpressionSetExample)  # a simple example is to transform the gene expression levels # of a given PhyloExpressionSet using a sqrt or log2 transformation  PES.sqrt <- tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample, sqrt)  PES.log2 <- tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample, log2)  # plotting the TAI using log2 transformed expression levels # and performing the Flat Line Test to obtain the p-value PlotSignature(ExpressionSet = tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample, log2),             permutations = 10,              type          = "l",              lwd           = 5,              TestStatistic = "FlatLineTest")    # in case the expression matrix contains 0s, a pseudocount can be added prior # to certain transformations, e.g. log2(x+1) where 1 is the pseudocount.  PhyloExpressionSetExample[4,3] = 0 PES.log2 <- tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample, log2, pseudocount = 0)  # this should return -Inf at PES.log2[4,3] the issue here is that  # -Inf cannot be used to compute the phylotranscriptomic profile.  PES.log2 <- tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample, log2, pseudocount = 1) # log2 transformed expression levels can now be used in downstream analyses.   # to perform rank transformation  PES.rank <- tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample, FUN = function(x) apply(x, 2, base::rank))   # rlog and vst transformations are now also possible by loading the DESeq2 package # and transforming the data with the parameter integerise = TRUE. library(DESeq2) # make sure the DESeq2 version >= 1.29.15 for rlog PES.vst <- tf(PhyloExpressionSetExample, vst, integerise = TRUE) } # }

what: Perform Permutation Tests Under Different Transformations — tfStability
title: Perform Permutation Tests Under Different Transformations — tfStability
text: tfStability aims statistically evaluate stability ReductiveHourglassTest, FlatLineTest, ReverseHourglassTest, EarlyConservationTest, LateConservationTest (based TAI TDI computations) different data transformations. corresponding p-value quantifies probability given TAI TDI pattern (phylotranscriptomics pattern) support chosen test. p-value < 0.05 indicates corresponding phylotranscriptomics pattern indeed support chosen test.

title: Perform Permutation Tests Under Different Transformations — tfStability
code: tfStability(   ExpressionSet,   TestStatistic = "FlatLineTest",   transforms = c("none", "sqrt", "log2", "rank", "squared"),   modules = NULL,   permutations = 1000,   pseudocount = 1 )

title: Perform Permutation Tests Under Different Transformations — tfStability
text: ExpressionSet standard PhyloExpressionSet DivergenceExpressionSet object. TestStatistic string defining type test statistics used quantify statistical significance present phylotranscriptomics pattern. Possible values can : TestStatistic = "FlatLineTest" : Statistical test deviation flat line TestStatistic = "ReductiveHourglassTest" : Statistical test existence hourglass shape (high-low-high pattern) TestStatistic = "ReverseHourglassTest" : Statistical test existence reverse hourglass pattern (low-high-low pattern) TestStatistic = "EarlyConservationTest" : Statistical test existence early conservation pattern (low-high-high pattern) TestStatistic = "LateConservationTest" : Statistical test existence late conservation pattern (high-high-low pattern) transforms character vector valid function transforms gene expression levels. modules list storing three elements: early, mid, late. element expects numeric vector specifying developmental stages experiments correspond module. example, module = list(early = 1:2, mid = 3:5, late = 6:7) divides dataset storing seven developmental stages 3 modules. permutations numeric value specifying number permutations performed FlatLineTest, EarlyConservationTest, LateConservationTest, ReductiveHourglassTest ReverseHourglassTest. pseudocount valid number add expression matrix prior log transformations.

title: Perform Permutation Tests Under Different Transformations — tfStability
text: vector object containing vector elements: p.value : p-value quantifying statistical significance (depending chosen test) given phylotranscriptomics pattern given data transformation(s).

New function PairwiseTest() : Statistically evaluate pairwise difference phylotranscriptomic pattern two contrasts based   computations. New function pairScore() : Compute pairwise difference TAI (TDI) score.

title: myTAI 1.0.1.9000
text: New function PlotSignatureTransformed() : Plot evolutionary signatures across transcriptomes RNA-seq transformations New function tfStability(): Perform Permutation Tests Different Transformations (test robustness p-values given test (e.g. FlatLineTest(), ReductiveHourglassTest(), ReverseHourglassTest(), EarlyConservationTest() LateConservationTest()) expression data transformations) New function LateConservationTest() : Perform Reductive Late Conservation Test (test high-mid-low (high-high-low) TAI TDI pattern) New function lcScore() : Compute Hourglass Score LateConservationTest internal rcpp functions now using Eigen automatically enable parallelization

title: myTAI 1.0.1.9000
